t 1425":"circa 1425","after 1480":"na 1480","1482":"1482","1480":"1480","1529":"1529","1516":"1516","England":"England","Mappowder, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Mappowder, Dorset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","West Coker, South Somerset, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"West Coker, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Mappowder, Dorset, England":"Mappowder, Dorset, England"},"en":{"about 1425–1500":"about 1425–1500","1425–1514":"1425–1514","1455–1529":"1455–1529","1480–Female":"1480–Deceased","1482–1516":"1482–1516","1425–1500":"1425–1500","1514":"1514","1425":"1425","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","about 1425":"about 1425","after 1480":"after 1480","1482":"1482","1480":"1480","1529":"1529","1516":"1516","England":"England","Mappowder, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Mappowder, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","West Coker, South Somerset, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"West Coker, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Mappowder, Dorset, England":"Mappowder, Dorset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mallett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Malot</i>, more rarely <i>Malet</i>, a pet form of   Mall  , <i>Mald</i> (i.e. Maud, Matilda) + the diminutive suffix <i>-ot</i> or <i>-et</i>. In post-medieval forms of the surname final <i>-ot</i> was generally altered to <i>-et(t)</i>. Though there are alternative Norman origins (see below), this is the usual source of the English surname.","English: of Norman origin, a nickname from Old French <i>maillet</i> ‘hammer’ (see   Maillet  , compare   Mallet   4), used as a battle weapon. Robert Malet, lord of the Honour of Eye (Suffolk) in 1086, was the son of William Malet of Graville-Sainte-Honorine (Seine-Maritime). The latter is referred to as Gulielmo agnomine <i>Mal(l)eto</i> ‘William, surnamed Mal(l)et’ in the late 11th-century Gesta Guillelmi of William of Poitiers and the early 12th-century Historia Ecclesia of Orderic Vitalis. According to tradition, this surname arose because of William's reputation for bludgeoning his enemies in battle <i>(cum) malleo</i> ‘with the hammer’. The story may be true or it may have been invented to explain the name, in which case see 3 below for an alternative etymology.","English: of Norman origin, from the Old French personal name <i>Malet</i>, a pet form of   Malo  . Compare   Mallet   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Mall","meanings":["English: from the medieval female personal name <i>Mall</i>, a common form of <i>Mald</i> or <i>Maud</i>. See also   Maude   and   Moll  . It had several pet forms; see   Malin  ,   Malkin  , and   Mallet  .","Indian (northern states): from Sanskrit <i>malla</i> ‘strongman, wrestler’."]},{"name":"Maillet","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Yvon, Emile, Ulysse, Alphee, Andre, Jean-Paul, Laurent, Normand, Alban, Alcide, Allain, Antoine.","French:","from Old French <i>maillet</i> ‘mallet’, used as a metonymic occupational name for someone who worked with such an implement, e.g. a smith, or as a nickname for a fearsome warrior (see English   Mallett   2)."]},{"name":"Maillot","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French:","from Old French <i>maillot</i> ‘big mallet’, used as a metonymic occupational name for someone who worked with such an implement, e.g. a smith, and perhaps also as a nickname for a fearsome warrior (see English   Mallett   2). This is the usual form of the surname in France (it is, however, most frequent in Réunion), while in North America it is normally spelled   Mailhot  ."]}]},{"name":"Avice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French form of the ancient Germanic name <i>Aveza</i>, derived from a short form of one or more compound names containing the first element <i>av</i> (as in   Ava ;  the meaning is uncertain). The correspondence in form to the Latin word <i>avis</i> ‘bird’ is coincidental."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":30,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Avice Mallett was born about 1425, in England. She had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with John Coker. She died in 1500, in West Coker, Somerset, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 76."},"et":{"about 1425–1500":"umbes 1425–1500","1425–1514":"1425–1514","1455–1529":"1455–1529","1480–Female":"1480–Surnud","1482–1516":"1482–1516","1425–1500":"1425–1500","1514":"1514","1425":"1425","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","about 1425":"umbes 1425","after 1480":"pärast 1480","1482":"1482","1480":"1480","1529":"1529","1516":"1516","England":"England","Mappowder, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Mappowder, Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","West Coker, South Somerset, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"West Coker, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Mappowder, Dorset, England":"Mappowder, Dorset, England"},"fi":{"about 1425–1500":"noin 1425–1500","1425–1514":"1425–1514","1455–1529":"1455–1529","1480–Female":"1480–Kuollut","1482–1516":"1482–1516","1425–1500":"1425–1500","1514":"1514","1425":"1425","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","about 1425":"noin 1425","after 1480":"1480 jälkeen","1482":"1482","1480":"1480","1529":"1529","1516":"1516","England":"England","Mappowder, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Mappowder, Dorset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","West Coker, South Somerset, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"West Coker, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta",